📦 1. Fetch Type (EAGER vs LAZY)
📌 Concept
Defines when related entities are loaded from the database.

⚙️ Approach
Types:
Fetch Type
Behavior
EAGER
Load immediately with parent
LAZY
Load only when accessed


💻 Code
@Entity
class User {
    @OneToMany(mappedBy = "user", fetch = FetchType.LAZY)
    private List<Order> orders;
}


🔑 Key Points
Default:
@OneToMany → LAZY ✅
@ManyToOne → EAGER ⚠️
LAZY uses proxy objects
Accessing LAZY outside transaction → ❌ LazyInitializationException

📘 Learnings
Prefer LAZY by default
Use EAGER only when always needed

🧹 2. Orphan Removal
📌 Concept
Deletes child entity if it is removed from parent collection.
👉 Not just DB delete — triggered by removing from Java object.

⚙️ Approach
Use orphanRemoval = true

💻 Code
@Entity
class User {
    @OneToMany(mappedBy = "user", cascade = CascadeType.ALL, orphanRemoval = true)
    private List<Order> orders;
}

user.getOrders().remove(order); // triggers DELETE in DB


🔑 Key Points
Works with collection relationships
Different from CascadeType.REMOVE
Helps avoid orphan records

📘 Learnings
Think: “If child is not linked → delete it”

🐢 3. N+1 Query Problem
📌 Concept
Occurs when Hibernate runs:
1 query for parent
N queries for each child
👉 Leads to performance issues

⚙️ Approach
Problem Example:
List<User> users = userRepo.findAll();

for(User u : users) {
    System.out.println(u.getOrders()); // triggers N queries
}


💻 Generated Queries
SELECT * FROM user;
SELECT * FROM orders WHERE user_id = 1;
SELECT * FROM orders WHERE user_id = 2;
...


🔑 Key Points
Happens mostly with LAZY loading
Very common in real projects ⚠️

📘 Learnings
Must optimize for scalability

⚡ 4. N+1 Query Optimization
📌 Concept
Reduce multiple queries into single optimized query

⚙️ Approach
✅ 1. Fetch Join (Best)
@Query("SELECT u FROM User u JOIN FETCH u.orders")
List<User> findAllUsersWithOrders();


✅ 2. Entity Graph
@EntityGraph(attributePaths = {"orders"})
List<User> findAll();


✅ 3. Batch Fetching
spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.default_batch_fetch_size=10


🔑 Key Points
Fetch Join → most powerful
Avoid blindly switching to EAGER ❌
Always monitor queries

📘 Learnings
Performance = key in backend
Always think in SQL, not just Java

🔗 5. JPQL vs Native Query (IMPORTANT)
📌 Concept
Two ways to write queries in Spring Data JPA

⚙️ Approach
Type
Description
JPQL
Works on Entity objects
Native
Works on actual SQL


💻 Code
// JPQL
@Query("SELECT u FROM User u WHERE u.name = :name")

// Native
@Query(value = "SELECT * FROM user WHERE name = ?", nativeQuery = true)


🔑 Key Points
JPQL is DB independent ✅
Native is more powerful but DB dependent ⚠️

📘 Learnings
Use JPQL for most cases
Native when needed (complex queries)

🧠 6. DTO Projection (Very Important for Performance)
📌 Concept
Fetch only required data instead of full entity

⚙️ Approach

💻 Code
@Query("SELECT new com.dto.UserDTO(u.name, u.email) FROM User u")
List<UserDTO> getUsers();


🔑 Key Points
Avoids unnecessary data loading
Improves performance
Best for APIs

📘 Learnings
Never expose full entities in APIs

⚠️ 7. LazyInitializationException
📌 Concept
Occurs when LAZY data accessed outside transaction

💻 Example
User user = userRepo.findById(id).get();
user.getOrders().size(); // ❌ outside transaction


🔑 Key Points
Happens when session is closed
Common beginner mistake

📘 Fixes
Use @Transactional
Use Fetch Join
Use DTO projection

